## Security baseline
- Treat all external input as untrusted (URL params, query strings, server JSON, WebSocket messages).
- Encode and sanitize when rendering untrusted text; default to safe patterns for XSS prevention.
- Apply least privilege for browser APIs and third-party scripts (CSP and dependency choices matter).

## Dependency management
- Use one package manager and lockfile consistently; commit the lockfile.
- Review dependency additions; prefer small, maintained packages.
- Prefer upgrading dependencies over pinning known-vulnerable versions without cause.
- Avoid unnecessary dependency bloat and duplicate major versions of the same ecosystem.

## Vulnerability management
- Run `npm audit`, `pnpm audit`, or the org’s SCA tool regularly and in CI where practical.
- Treat reachable vulnerabilities as release-blocking unless explicitly risk-accepted.
- Reassess vulnerable transitive dependencies promptly.

## Transport and cookies
- Use HTTPS in production; never send credentials or tokens over plain HTTP.
- Prefer `HttpOnly`, `Secure`, and `SameSite` cookies when using cookie-based auth; avoid storing tokens in `localStorage` unless threat-modeled.

## Secrets
- Never commit secrets, API keys, tokens, or private certificates.
- Load secrets from the build environment or runtime injection appropriate to the deployment model.
